 people: I used to think that using local labels was<br />a great idea, but I'm not all that certain any more.  The problem is<br />that gcc seems to implement local labels through a similar mechanism as<br />local functions, which in turn means that any function that has a local<br />label will aqcuire a stack frame.  No, don't ask me why, but that is<br />what seems to happen. <br /><br />End result: avoid local labels if you really care about that last bit of<br />performance<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
